04142nam a22006015i 9780822374886DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20152015ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015020933  a97808223748867 a10.1515/97808223748862doi  a(DE-B1597)551790  a(OCoLC)921306869  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aGT525b.P44 2015 4aGT525b.P44 2015 7aDES0050002bisacsh04a391.00952231 aPham, Minh-Ha T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAsians Wear Clothes on the Internet :bRace, Gender, and the Work of Personal Style Blogging /cMinh-Ha T. Pham. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b38 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Asian Personal Style Superbloggers and the Material Conditions and Contexts of Asian Fashion Work -- tChapter 1. The Taste and Aftertaste for Asian Superbloggers -- tChapter 2. Style Stories, Written Tastes, and the Work of Self-Composure -- tChapter 3. "So Many and All the Same" (but Not Quite): Outfit Photos and the Codes of Asian Eliteness -- tChapter 4. The Racial and Gendered Job Performances of Fashion Blogger Poses -- tChapter 5. Invisible Labor and Racial Visibilities in Outfit Posts -- tCoda. All in the Eyes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the first ever book devoted to a critical investigation of the personal style blogosphere, Minh-Ha T. Pham examines the phenomenal rise of elite Asian bloggers who have made a career of posting photographs of themselves wearing clothes on the Internet. Pham understands their online activities as "taste work" practices that generate myriad forms of capital for superbloggers and the brands they feature. A multifaceted and detailed analysis, Asians Wear Clothes on the Internet addresses questions concerning the status and meaning of "Asian taste" in the early twenty-first century, the kinds of cultural and economic work Asian tastes do, and the fashion public and industry's appetite for certain kinds of racialized eliteness. Situating blogging within the historical context of gendered and racialized fashion work while being attentive to the broader cultural, technological, and economic shifts in global consumer capitalism, Asians Wear Clothes on the Internet has profound implications for understanding the changing and enduring dynamics of race, gender, and class in shaping some of the most popular work practices and spaces of the digital fashion media economy.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAsiansxClothingxBlogs. 0aFashion writingxBlogsxAsia. 0aFashion writingzAsiaxBlogs. 0aFashionxSocial aspectsxBlogsxAsia. 0aFashionxSocial aspectszAsiaxBlogs. 7aDESIGN / Fashion & Accessories.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374886zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374886423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374886.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles